of the session.&lt;/p&gt;
</description><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">ankur</dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 07 Oct 2017 14:19:10 +0100</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="false">tag:ankursinha.in,2017-10-07:/2017/10/07/fedora-classroom-git-101-report.html</guid><category>Community</category><category>Fedora</category><category>Git</category><category>Planet</category></item><item><title>Fedora Classroom: Command Line 101: report</title><link>http://ankursinha.in/2017/08/10/fedora-classroom-command-line-101-report.html</link><description>&lt;p class="first last"&gt;I taught a &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://fedoraproject.org/wiki/Classroom"&gt;Fedora classroom&lt;/a&gt; session today - &amp;quot;Command Line 101&amp;quot; - where I introduced the command line and demonstrated how useful the command line is. This is a quick summary of the session.&lt;/p&gt;
</description><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">ankur</dc:creator><pubDate>Thu, 10 Aug 2017 23:03:24 +0100</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="false">tag:ankursinha.in,2017-08-10:/2017/08/10/fedora-classroom-command-line-101-report.html</guid><category>Bash</category><category>Blog</category><category>Community</category><category>Linux</category><category>Planet</category><category>Fedora</category></item><item><title>Bringing together Gitter, IRC, and Slack channels in one place on Riot</title><link>http://ankursinha.in/2017/07/12/bringing-together-gitter-irc-and-slack-channels-in-one-place-on-riot.html</link><description>&lt;p class="first last"&gt;Different teams use different platforms to communicate within themselves. When teams on different communication platforms want to collaborate, though - there's a bit of an issue. In this post, I document how one can setup channels on various platforms (&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://slack.com"&gt;Slack&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_Relay_Chat"&gt;IRC&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://gitter.im"&gt;Gitter&lt;/a&gt;) and bring them all together on &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://riot.im"&gt;Riot&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
</description><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">ankur</dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 12 Jul 2017 13:55:17 +0100</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="false">tag:ankursinha.in,2017-07-12:/2017/07/12/bringing-together-gitter-irc-and-slack-channels-in-one-place-on-riot.html</guid><category>Community</category><category>Computational neuroscience</category><category>Fedora</category><category>FlatPak</category><category>Free software</category><category>Gitter</category><category>Linux</category><category>Planet</category></item><item><title>A channel for neuroscientists on Gitter</title><link>http://ankursinha.in/2017/06/26/a-channel-for-neuroscientists-on-gitter.html</link><description>&lt;p class="first last"&gt;I've come across a few mailing lists for neuroscientists, but I couldn't find a chat channel. While mailing lists suit certain purposes, open source communities tend to use a combination of mailing lists and chat channels - each platform serves different purposes. TLDR: here's a new chat channel on &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://github.com/gitterHQ"&gt;Gitter&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://gitter.im/neuroscience-central/Lobby"&gt;here&lt;/a&gt; for everything neuroscience related. It is also accessible using the &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://webchat.freenode.net/?channels=#neuroscience-central-lobby"&gt;IRC&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://riot.im/app/#/room/#neuroscience-central-lobby:matrix.org"&gt;Riot&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
</description><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">ankur</dc:creator><pubDate>Mon, 26 Jun 2017 10:30:01 +0100</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="false">tag:ankursinha.in,2017-06-26:/2017/06/26/a-channel-for-neuroscientists-on-gitter.html</guid><category>Community</category><category>Computational neuroscience</category><category>Gitter</category><category>Planet</category></item><item><title>Using Wallabag to manage your online reading list</title><link>http://ankursinha.in/2017/02/28/using-wallabag-to-manage-your-online-reading-list.html</link><description>&lt;p class="first last"&gt;I've recently begun using &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://wallabag.org/en"&gt;Wallabag&lt;/a&gt; to manage my reading list. It is released under the &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://tldrlegal.com/license/mit-license"&gt;MIT license&lt;/a&gt;, so it's &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://www.gnu.org/philosophy/free-sw.en.html"&gt;Free software&lt;/a&gt; too!&lt;/p&gt;
</description><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">ankur</dc:creator><pubDate>Tue, 28 Feb 2017 20:52:40 +0000</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="false">tag:ankursinha.in,2017-02-28:/2017/02/28/using-wallabag-to-manage-your-online-reading-list.html</guid><category>Fedora</category><category>Wallabag</category><category>Planet</category><category>Reading</category></item></channel></rss>